title: For Sale:  Ed Brown Special Forces Carry 1911
postcontent: This was purchase as a gift to myself.  You know how there's always that high dollar piece that becomes a prize to you.  Well, in any case, it kinda went somewhat sour for me, hence why I'm getting rid of it.  I purchased this BRAND NEW on July 31, 2016 from a local gun boutique.  Yes a brand new purchase.  It was was never fired, and as with all their other models, this was on display in their glass case.  Anyway, I went home and saw blemishes on the finish.  Long story short, within less than 24 hours of owning it, I had it taken back to the store and sent into Ed Brown to have it refinished.  As you can see in my photos, there's a receipt for the original gun purchase, and a receipt for the refinishing for $295.  Took forever to get it back to me since---I don't wanna talk about it. So add the numbers up from the receipt and this piece is over 3k (hence the "sour" part).  It was also originally Stealth Grey and I had it refinished in Stealth Grey.Fast forward 3 months after it came back, and after 600 rounds total through it, the finish started wearing again on the slide.  i was hoping I would be able to have some sort of a warranty or a discount second time around.  Nope.  In any case, I was gonna sell it as-is just to get rid of it.  But decided to have it made into stainless, since Ed Brown 1911s can be easily changed to any color or stainless steel if you would like.  They even offer that on their website, and apparently, many people send their 1911s back to make into Stainless Steel when they don't want to deal with the wear anymore.  Well, so here I go trying to get it to stainless.  I didn't like their satin stainless finish, so I had it polished a step further into a higher polished stainless.  It looks a million times better than the Stealth Grey, and never will I have to deal with the finish coming off again.  WOW, that was a novel.Looking to sell this pistol.  If you're looking for a trade, I will consider something a bit more than what I'm asking, since that seems to be the trend on "trading".Gun is in EXCELLENT condition.  It has a total of less than 800 rounds through it.  For a custom 1911, this is BARELY broken in.  Yes, UNDER 800 rounds.  The internals look brand new if you open it up.  If you would like to see the inside, I will gladly open it up for you to inspect.  Yes, this gun is almost in brand spanking new condition.  Most of the custom 1911 you find on here will have thousands and thousands of rounds through them. This is again, barely broken into.As seen in the photos, I have the original receipt and the receipt when I went to get it refinished the first time.  This is something very common for Ed Brown owners apparently.  It came with only ONE magazine.  Yes, Ed Brown 1911s only ship with 1 magazine.  And I NEVER used the mag.  Other than the gun, everything that came inside the package was never touched.  I don't use any mag other than the Wilson Combat 47d mags or Chip McCormick Power 10.Please text me: (28l) 773-82 SlX NlnE.

The butt plate is the original Winchester plate. The plate has some light marks, and there is a small chip missing on the bottom edge. The forend has some light impressions, but no chips or cracks. The checkering on the forend and buttstock are worn, but prominent. The bluing on this gun is worn. The barrel retains the majority of the original bluing. The left side of the barrel shows more wear. The barrel band is heavily worn, and only retains blue around the swivel. The bluing on the receiver is heavily worn. The majority of the remaining bluing is around the saddle ring. The barrel is fitted with a Winchester Express sight with three ranging leaves. The barrel is 20 inches and has a slight taper. The bore is a little frosty, but the rifling is still prominent. Overall the gun still looks good. The gun is over 100 years old, and shows some honest wear. The action is smooth and the gun locks up tight. The hammer spring is strong, and the trigger is crisp.
